Lea, I've verified the updated CSS. Most of the changes are excellent -- the double-ring focus technique, forced-colors support, clip fallback, contrast ratio documentation, and semantic color comments are all spot-on. Well done.

Two issues I'm still seeing:

**1. `--color-fg-muted` is still gray-500, not gray-600.**
Line 212: `--color-fg-muted: var(--color-gray-500);`
You mentioned bumping it to gray-600, but the CSS still references gray-500. This needs to be `var(--color-gray-600)` for the comfortable 7:1 contrast ratio. The current 4.6:1 is technically passing but one rounding error from failure. Can you update this?

**2. Skip link focus reveal is still missing.**
The `.visually-hidden` class clips content off-screen, which is correct for screen-reader-only content. But our skip link (`<a href="#main-content" class="visually-hidden">Skip to main content</a>`) needs to become VISIBLE when it receives keyboard focus. Without a focus rule, a keyboard user tabs to it and sees nothing -- the link is there but invisible.

We need either a modifier on `.visually-hidden` or a separate `.skip-link` class. I'd recommend a separate class in the utilities layer:

```css
/* Skip link -- visually hidden until focused, then appears at top of page.
 * Used for the "Skip to main content" link (WCAG 2.4.1). */
.skip-link {
  position: absolute;
  inline-size: 1px;
  block-size: 1px;
  padding: 0;
  margin: -1px;
  overflow: hidden;
  clip: rect(0 0 0 0);
  clip-path: inset(50%);
  white-space: nowrap;
  border: 0;

  &:focus {
    position: fixed;
    inset-block-start: var(--space-sm);
    inset-inline-start: var(--space-sm);
    inline-size: auto;
    block-size: auto;
    padding: var(--space-sm) var(--space-md);
    margin: 0;
    overflow: visible;
    clip: auto;
    clip-path: none;
    white-space: normal;
    background-color: var(--color-bg-raised);
    color: var(--color-primary);
    font-weight: var(--font-semibold);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-md);
    z-index: 9999;
  }
}
```

This positions the skip link as a floating pill at the top-left when focused, then it disappears again when focus moves on. It's a standard pattern used by gov.uk, GitHub, and most accessibility-conscious sites.

Everything else in the update is solid. These two items and we're done with the foundation.

